{"title_page": "Hugo Boss (fashion designer)", "text_new": "{{about|the fashion designer|the eponymous clothing company he founded|Hugo Boss|comedian Hugo Boss|Joe Lycett}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Hugo Ferdinand Boss\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = Hugo Ferdinand Boss\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1885|07|08|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Metzingen]], [[Kingdom of W\u00fcrttemberg]], [[German Empire]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1948|08|09|1885|07|08|df=yes}}\n| death_place = Metzingen, [[Allied-occupied Germany|Germany]]\n| nationality = German\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = Founding [[Hugo Boss]] Luxury clothing company\n| occupation  = {{hlist|Fashion designer|entrepreneur}}\n| Rank        = Corporal\n|party        = [[Nazi Party]]\n|footnotes    = \n}}\n'''Hugo Ferdinand Boss''' (8 July 1885 &ndash; 9 August 1948){{cn|date=April 2020}} was a [[Germans|German]] [[fashion designer]], anti-semite and businessman. He was the founder of the clothing company [[Hugo Boss|Hugo Boss AG]]. He was an active member of the [[Nazi Party]] as early as 1931 and remained loyal to the [[Nazi German]] ideology throughout the duration of the party's existence.\n\n==Early life==\nBoss was born in [[Metzingen]], in the [[Kingdom of W\u00fcrttemberg]], to Luise (n\u00e9e M\u00fcnzenmayer) and Heinrich Boss,<ref>{{cite web|title=Hugo Ferdinand Boss|website=Geneall.net|url=http://www.geneall.net/D/per_page.php?id=481001}}</ref> the youngest of five children. He performed an [[apprenticeship]] as a merchant, completed military service from 1903 to 1905 and worked in a weaving mill in [[Konstanz]]. He then took over as the heir to his parents' lingerie shop in Metzingen in 1908.{{cn|date=April 2020}} In 1914, he was mobilized into the army and he served through [[World War I]] with the rank of [[corporal]].{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Personal life==\nBoss married Anna Katharina Freysinger in 1908. They had one daughter.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Hugo Boss company==\nHe founded his own clothing company in Metzingen in 1923 and then a factory in 1924, initially with two partners. The company produced shirts and jackets and then work clothing, sportswear and raincoats. In the 1930s, it produced uniforms for the [[Sturmabteilung|SA]], the [[Schutzstaffel|SS]],<ref>Lumsden, Robin. ''A Collector's Guide To: The Allgemeine - SS'', [[Ian Allan Publishing|Ian Allan Publishing, Inc.]] 2001, p 53.</ref> the [[Hitler Youth]], the postal service, rail employees and later the [[Wehrmacht]].<ref name=local-2011>{{cite news|date=2011-09-21|title=Hugo Boss comes clean on Nazi past|work=[[The Local]]|url=https://www.thelocal.de/20110921/37729|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20170323224959/https://www.thelocal.de/20110921/37729|archivedate=2017-03-23}}\n</ref>\n\n==Support of Nazism==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 146-2008-0276, Hans Heinrich Lammers.jpg|thumb|225px|upright|[[SS-Gruppenf\u00fchrer]] [[Hans Heinrich Lammers]] in black ''[[Allgemeine-SS]]'' uniform 1938]]\nBoss joined the Nazi Party in 1931, two years before [[Adolf Hitler]] came to power.<ref name=abcarticledirectory-Hugo-Boss-Biography>{{cite news|url=http://www.abcarticledirectory.com/Article/Hugo-Boss-Biography/933303|title=Hugo Boss Biography}}</ref> By the third quarter of 1932, the all-black [[Uniforms and insignia of the Schutzstaffel|SS uniform]] (to replace the [[Uniforms and insignia of the Sturmabteilung|SA brown shirts]]) was designed by ''[[SS-Oberf\u00fchrer]]'' Prof. [[Karl Diebitsch]], graphic designer Walter Heck, who had no affiliation with the company.<ref>McNab, Chris. ''Hitler's Elite: The SS 1939\u201345'', Osprey 2013, p 90.</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Hugo Boss apology for Nazi past as book is published |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-15008682 |website=BBC News |publisher=BBC |accessdate=2 October 2018 |date=21 September 2011}}</ref> The [[Hugo Boss]] company produced these black uniforms along with the brown [[Sturmabteilung|SA]] shirts and the black-and-brown uniforms of the Hitler Youth.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B00E4DF153FF936A2575BC0A961958260 |title=Hugo Boss Acknowledges Link to Nazi Regime |date=1997-08-15|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2008-09-25}}</ref><ref>White, Constance C. R. \"Patterns:  Dealing with Hugo Boss's Nazi tie.\"  ''The New York Times'' 19 August 1997:  A20.</ref> Some workers were [[French people|French]] and [[Polish people|Polish]] [[prisoners of war]] [[Forced labour under German rule during World War II|forced into labour]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1997/aug/15/news/ls-22533|title=Clothier Made Nazi Uniforms|last=Givhan|first=Robin |authorlink=Robin Givhan|date=1997-08-15|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=2008-11-08}}</ref><ref name=\"7 Die Firma Hugo Boss\"/> In 1999, US lawyers acting on behalf of [[Holocaust survivors]] started legal proceedings against the Hugo Boss company over the use of slave labour during the war.<ref>{{cite news\n |accessdate=2011-10-03 |date=May 15, 1999 |newspaper=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]\n |location=[[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]] |last=Hall |first=Allan <!-- probably not subj of article -->\n |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Hugo+Boss+facing+Holocaust+lawsuit.-a060421770\n |title=Hugo Boss facing Holocaust lawsuit}}</ref> The misuse of 140 Polish and 40 French forced workers led to an apology by the company.<ref>{{cite web|last=Abramovitch |first=Seth |title=Hugo Boss Apologizes For Making Nazis Look Fabulous |url=http://gawker.com/5843124/hugo-boss-apologizes-for-making-nazis-look-fabulous |accessdate=4 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130328012506/http://gawker.com/5843124/hugo-boss-apologizes-for-making-nazis-look-fabulous |archivedate=28 March 2013 }}</ref>\n\nAfter [[World War II]], the [[denazification]] process saw Boss initially labeled as an \"[[activist]], supporter and beneficiary\" of National Socialism, which resulted in a heavy fine, also stripping him of his voting rights and of his capacity to run a business. However, this initial ruling was appealed, and Boss was re-labeled as a \"follower\", a category with a less severe punishment.<ref name=abcarticledirectory-Hugo-Boss-Biography/> Nevertheless, the effects of the ban led to Boss's son-in-law, Eugen Holy, taking over both the ownership and the running of the company.\n\n==Death==\nBoss died of a [[dental abscess|tooth abscess]] in 1948.<ref name=\"7 Die Firma Hugo Boss\">{{in lang|de}} Zwangsarbeit in Metzingen (Forced Work in Metzingen), [http://www.metzingen-zwangsarbeit.de/Kober-Studie/7_Die_Firma_Hugo_Boss/body_7_die_firma_hugo_boss.html Ch.7: Die Firma Hugo Boss]</ref>\n\n{{Portal|Biography|Germany|Fashion}}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb name|0098069}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boss, Hugo}}\n[[Category:1885 births]]\n[[Category:1948 deaths]]\n[[Category:F\u00f6rderndes Mitglied der SS]]\n[[Category:German chief executives]]\n[[Category:German company founders]]\n[[Category:German fashion businesspeople]]\n[[Category:German fashion designers]]\n[[Category:German military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Menswear designers]]\n[[Category:Nazi Party members]]\n[[Category:People from Metzingen]]\n[[Category:People from the Kingdom of W\u00fcrttemberg]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the fashion designer|the eponymous clothing company he founded|Hugo Boss}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Hugo Ferdinand Boss\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = Hugo Ferdinand Boss\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1885|07|08|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Metzingen]], [[Kingdom of W\u00fcrttemberg]], [[German Empire]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1948|08|09|1885|07|08|df=yes}}\n| death_place = Metzingen, [[Allied-occupied Germany|Germany]]\n| nationality = German\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = Founding [[Hugo Boss]] Luxury clothing company\n| occupation  = {{hlist|Fashion designer|entrepreneur}}\n| Rank        = Corporal\n|party        = [[Nazi Party]]\n|footnotes    = \n}}\n'''Hugo Ferdinand Boss''' (8 July 1885 &ndash; 9 August 1948){{cn|date=April 2020}} was a [[Germans|German]] [[fashion designer]], anti-semite and businessman. He was the founder of the clothing company [[Hugo Boss|Hugo Boss AG]]. He was an active member of the [[Nazi Party]] as early as 1931 and remained loyal to the [[Nazi German]] ideology throughout the duration of the party's existence.\n\n==Early life==\nBoss was born in [[Metzingen]], in the [[Kingdom of W\u00fcrttemberg]], to Luise (n\u00e9e M\u00fcnzenmayer) and Heinrich Boss,<ref>{{cite web|title=Hugo Ferdinand Boss|website=Geneall.net|url=http://www.geneall.net/D/per_page.php?id=481001}}</ref> the youngest of five children. He performed an [[apprenticeship]] as a merchant, completed military service from 1903 to 1905 and worked in a weaving mill in [[Konstanz]]. He then took over as the heir to his parents' lingerie shop in Metzingen in 1908.{{cn|date=April 2020}} In 1914, he was mobilized into the army and he served through [[World War I]] with the rank of [[corporal]].{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Personal life==\nBoss married Anna Katharina Freysinger in 1908. They had one daughter.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Hugo Boss company==\nHe founded his own clothing company in Metzingen in 1923 and then a factory in 1924, initially with two partners. The company produced shirts and jackets and then work clothing, sportswear and raincoats. In the 1930s, it produced uniforms for the [[Sturmabteilung|SA]], the [[Schutzstaffel|SS]],<ref>Lumsden, Robin. ''A Collector's Guide To: The Allgemeine - SS'', [[Ian Allan Publishing|Ian Allan Publishing, Inc.]] 2001, p 53.</ref> the [[Hitler Youth]], the postal service, rail employees and later the [[Wehrmacht]].<ref name=local-2011>{{cite news|date=2011-09-21|title=Hugo Boss comes clean on Nazi past|work=[[The Local]]|url=https://www.thelocal.de/20110921/37729|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20170323224959/https://www.thelocal.de/20110921/37729|archivedate=2017-03-23}}\n</ref>\n\n==Support of Nazism==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 146-2008-0276, Hans Heinrich Lammers.jpg|thumb|225px|upright|[[SS-Gruppenf\u00fchrer]] [[Hans Heinrich Lammers]] in black ''[[Allgemeine-SS]]'' uniform 1938]]\nBoss joined the Nazi Party in 1931, two years before [[Adolf Hitler]] came to power.<ref name=abcarticledirectory-Hugo-Boss-Biography>{{cite news|url=http://www.abcarticledirectory.com/Article/Hugo-Boss-Biography/933303|title=Hugo Boss Biography}}</ref> By the third quarter of 1932, the all-black [[Uniforms and insignia of the Schutzstaffel|SS uniform]] (to replace the [[Uniforms and insignia of the Sturmabteilung|SA brown shirts]]) was designed by ''[[SS-Oberf\u00fchrer]]'' Prof. [[Karl Diebitsch]], graphic designer Walter Heck, who had no affiliation with the company.<ref>McNab, Chris. ''Hitler's Elite: The SS 1939\u201345'', Osprey 2013, p 90.</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Hugo Boss apology for Nazi past as book is published |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-15008682 |website=BBC News |publisher=BBC |accessdate=2 October 2018 |date=21 September 2011}}</ref> The [[Hugo Boss]] company produced these black uniforms along with the brown [[Sturmabteilung|SA]] shirts and the black-and-brown uniforms of the Hitler Youth.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B00E4DF153FF936A2575BC0A961958260 |title=Hugo Boss Acknowledges Link to Nazi Regime |date=1997-08-15|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2008-09-25}}</ref><ref>White, Constance C. R. \"Patterns:  Dealing with Hugo Boss's Nazi tie.\"  ''The New York Times'' 19 August 1997:  A20.</ref> Some workers were [[French people|French]] and [[Polish people|Polish]] [[prisoners of war]] [[Forced labour under German rule during World War II|forced into labour]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1997/aug/15/news/ls-22533|title=Clothier Made Nazi Uniforms|last=Givhan|first=Robin |authorlink=Robin Givhan|date=1997-08-15|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=2008-11-08}}</ref><ref name=\"7 Die Firma Hugo Boss\"/> In 1999, US lawyers acting on behalf of [[Holocaust survivors]] started legal proceedings against the Hugo Boss company over the use of slave labour during the war.<ref>{{cite news\n |accessdate=2011-10-03 |date=May 15, 1999 |newspaper=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]\n |location=[[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]] |last=Hall |first=Allan <!-- probably not subj of article -->\n |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Hugo+Boss+facing+Holocaust+lawsuit.-a060421770\n |title=Hugo Boss facing Holocaust lawsuit}}</ref> The misuse of 140 Polish and 40 French forced workers led to an apology by the company.<ref>{{cite web|last=Abramovitch |first=Seth |title=Hugo Boss Apologizes For Making Nazis Look Fabulous |url=http://gawker.com/5843124/hugo-boss-apologizes-for-making-nazis-look-fabulous |accessdate=4 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130328012506/http://gawker.com/5843124/hugo-boss-apologizes-for-making-nazis-look-fabulous |archivedate=28 March 2013 }}</ref>\n\nAfter [[World War II]], the [[denazification]] process saw Boss initially labeled as an \"[[activist]], supporter and beneficiary\" of National Socialism, which resulted in a heavy fine, also stripping him of his voting rights and of his capacity to run a business. However, this initial ruling was appealed, and Boss was re-labeled as a \"follower\", a category with a less severe punishment.<ref name=abcarticledirectory-Hugo-Boss-Biography/> Nevertheless, the effects of the ban led to Boss's son-in-law, Eugen Holy, taking over both the ownership and the running of the company.\n\n==Death==\nBoss died of a [[dental abscess|tooth abscess]] in 1948.<ref name=\"7 Die Firma Hugo Boss\">{{in lang|de}} Zwangsarbeit in Metzingen (Forced Work in Metzingen), [http://www.metzingen-zwangsarbeit.de/Kober-Studie/7_Die_Firma_Hugo_Boss/body_7_die_firma_hugo_boss.html Ch.7: Die Firma Hugo Boss]</ref>\n\n{{Portal|Biography|Germany|Fashion}}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb name|0098069}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boss, Hugo}}\n[[Category:1885 births]]\n[[Category:1948 deaths]]\n[[Category:F\u00f6rderndes Mitglied der SS]]\n[[Category:German chief executives]]\n[[Category:German company founders]]\n[[Category:German fashion businesspeople]]\n[[Category:German fashion designers]]\n[[Category:German military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Menswear designers]]\n[[Category:Nazi Party members]]\n[[Category:People from Metzingen]]\n[[Category:People from the Kingdom of W\u00fcrttemberg]]\n", "name_user": "Nixrin", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added to header to reflect the comedian formerly known Joe Lycett change of name to Hugo Boss", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugo_Boss_(fashion_designer)"}
